// A STUN server is a small helper server used in internet calls or real-time apps (like video calls, voice chat, or WebRTC) to help two devices find each other on the internet. 
// Normally, your phone or laptop is connected through a Wi-Fi router, which hides your real internet address (public IP) and gives you a private one. 
// Because of this, other devices cannot directly connect to you. A STUN server solves this by telling your device what its public IP address and port look like from the internet side.

// Here is a simple example: imagine two friends, Rahul and Aman, want to talk directly through a video call. 
// Both are inside their own houses (routers). 
// They don’t know their outside house address, only their room number. 
// So each of them first asks a STUN server, “How do I look from outside?” The STUN server replies with their public internet address. Once both know this information, they can connect directly to each other for the call.

// So in simple words: a STUN server is like a helper that tells your device its real internet address so two users can connect directly without sending all data through a middle server.

